::section{#introduction}
::meta
type: introduction
summary: "Brief background on the role of the incretin system in glucose regulation and the need for new oral therapies."
::

# Introduction

The incretin system plays a vital role in maintaining postprandial glucose 
levels through the action of glucagon-like peptide-1 (GLP-1) and 
glucose-dependent insulinotropic polypeptide (GIP) @cite{drucker2006, holst2007}. 
These hormones are rapidly degraded by DPP-4.

::endsection


::section{#methods}
::meta
type: methods
summary: "Study design, participant selection, and dosage of the novel inhibitor WP-450."
::

# Material and Methods

A total of 250 patients with inadequately controlled Type 2 Diabetes (HbA1c 7.5-9.5%) 
were enrolled. Participants were randomized to receive either 50 mg of 
WP-450 or a placebo once daily.

::endsection


::section{#results}
::meta
type: results
summary: "Clinical outcomes including HbA1c reduction and adverse event reporting."
depends_on: ["#methods"]
::

# Results

The primary endpoint was the change in HbA1c from baseline to week 12.

::chart{#tbl-clinical-outcomes}
::title Primary and secondary clinical endpoints at week 12
::interpretation
WP-450 showed a statistically significant reduction in HbA1c (-1.2%) 
compared to the placebo group (+0.1%). Furthermore, 65% of the WP-450 group 
achieved the target HbA1c level of <7.0%.
::
| Variable | Baseline | Week 12 | Change | p-value |
|----------|----------|---------|--------|---------|
| HbA1c (%) - WP-450 | 8.4 | 7.2 | -1.2 | <0.001 |
| HbA1c (%) - Placebo | 8.3 | 8.4 | +0.1 | 0.45 |
| Fasting Glucose (mg/dL) - WP-450 | 165 | 135 | -30 | <0.001 |
| Fasting Glucose (mg/dL) - Placebo | 162 | 164 | +2 | 0.60 |
::endchart

::figure{#fig-adverse-events}
::file plot_ae.png
::description
This bar chart displays the frequency of the most common adverse events. 
Treatment-emergent adverse events (TEAEs) include nausea, headache, 
and nasopharyngitis.
::
::interpretation
The incidence of nausea was slightly higher in the WP-450 group (8%) 
compared to the placebo group (4%), but was generally mild and 
did not lead to discontinuation.
::
::endfigure

::endsection


::section{#discussion}
::meta
type: conclusion
summary: "Summary of clinical efficacy and safety of WP-450."
depends_on: ["#results"]
::

# Discussion and Conclusion

The small molecule inhibitor WP-450 is a promising new oral therapy 
for the management of Type 2 Diabetes. Its efficacy in lowering HbA1c 
is comparable to existing injectable GLP-1 agonists, with a favorable 
safety profile.

::endsection
